---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import EAIUtilityBar from '../components/EAIUtilityBar.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import PrepublicationFooter from '../components/PrepublicationFooter.astro';
import ReferenceDesk from '../components/ReferenceDesk.astro';
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="America's School Trust Library — An evidentiary archive of America's school trust lands and funds"
      description="Lands and funds set aside since 1785 to support America's public K-12 schools."
    />
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-archive-paper text-ink mode-library">
    <EAIUtilityBar />
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-5xl p-4 sm:p-8">
      <section class="home-declaration" aria-labelledby="home-declaration-heading">
        <h1 id="home-declaration-heading" class="home-declaration__title">
          America's School Trust Library
        </h1>
        <p class="home-declaration__subtitle">
          An evidentiary archive of America's school trust lands and funds
        </p>
        <p class="home-declaration__manifesto">
          <span class="home-declaration__manifesto-line">A forever gift, to forever schools, for a forever democracy.</span>
          <span class="home-declaration__manifesto-attr">— Margaret Bird's phrase (quoted here as her words; not an endorsement of this preview).</span>
        </p>
        <p class="home-declaration__paragraph">
          The schoolchildren of 1859 were promised an endowment. So were the children
          in classrooms today; so are the children for whom the corpus was pledged in
          perpetuity. America's 240-year school-trust record shows what the
          architecture of such a promise requires — codified fiduciary duties,
          restoration mechanisms, specialized legal defense, mandatory trustee
          education — and one piece without which the rest is decorative: a standing
          community of citizens, parents, advocates, journalists, and watchdog
          officials, across every party, who treat the architecture as binding across
          generations. That community is built one way. Margaret Bird's words:
          <em>"Increase the revenue to schools, get it directly to every single school
          where the parents, the teachers, and the principal are deciding how the
          money is implemented. And all of a sudden, you have built a huge
          constituency."</em> The Utah school trust grew thirty-fold under that
          discipline; the legislature is again trying to divert it; the watchful crew
          is again defending it. The architects of the next forever-institutions —
          climate trusts, sovereign wealth for the unborn, AI-targeting authorities —
          are designing in the present tense. The school-trust record is the only
          worked existence proof of the principle they need.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="home-poster home-poster--top mt-6" aria-label="The Library's argument in one image">
        <a href="/why/" class="block home-poster__link">
          <img
            src="/img/hero/hero_v1_2026-05-06.png"
            alt="Three-panel diagram: 1785 the experiment begins; 240 years of drift; 2026 the architects of the next century's trusts."
            class="w-full rounded-md shadow-md home-poster__img"
          />
        </a>
        <details class="home-poster__expander mt-2">
          <summary>View full poster</summary>
          <a href="/img/hero/hero_v1_2026-05-06.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="block mt-2">
            <img
              src="/img/hero/hero_v1_2026-05-06.png"
              alt="Three-panel diagram, expanded view: 1785 the experiment begins; 240 years of drift; 2026 the architects of the next century's trusts."
              class="w-full rounded-md shadow-md home-poster__img--full"
            />
          </a>
        </details>
        <p class="mt-3 text-center text-sm italic text-slate-600">
          <a href="/why/" class="text-blue-700 underline">Why this matters →</a>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="home-doors mt-10" aria-label="Three doors into the Library">
        <ul class="home-doors__grid">
          <li class="home-door home-door--1">
            <a href="/reading/" class="home-door__link">
              <span class="home-door__icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                  <path d="M12 7v14"/>
                  <path d="M3 18a1 1 0 0 1-1-1V4a1 1 0 0 1 1-1h5a4 4 0 0 1 4 4 4 4 0 0 1 4-4h5a1 1 0 0 1 1 1v13a1 1 0 0 1-1 1h-6a3 3 0 0 0-3 3 3 3 0 0 0-3-3z"/>
                </svg>
              </span>
              <h2 class="home-door__heading">Door 1 — Understand the Argument</h2>
              <p class="home-door__subtitle">
                How the school-trust experiment teaches what every long-horizon institution
                must engineer for — and what it cannot.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
          <li class="home-door home-door--2">
            <a href="/atlas/" class="home-door__link">
              <span class="home-door__icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                  <circle cx="11" cy="11" r="8"/>
                  <path d="m21 21-4.3-4.3"/>
                </svg>
              </span>
              <h2 class="home-door__heading">Door 2 — Find the Evidence</h2>
              <p class="home-door__subtitle">
                The case-by-case record of how trusts drift, get captured, get hijacked —
                across 240 years and fifty states.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
          <li class="home-door home-door--3">
            <a href="/the-watchful-crew/" class="home-door__link">
              <span class="home-door__icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                  <path d="M16 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"/>
                  <circle cx="9" cy="7" r="4"/>
                  <path d="M22 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-3-3.87"/>
                  <path d="M16 3.13a4 4 0 0 1 0 7.75"/>
                </svg>
              </span>
              <h2 class="home-door__heading">Door 3 — Join the Watchful Crew</h2>
              <p class="home-door__subtitle">
                Named offices, bounded missions, public stewardship. The watchdog citizens,
                school-board members, journalists, and lawyers without which the seven anchors
                are decorative.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <aside class="launch-announcement mt-10">
        <span class="eyebrow">New</span>
        <p>
          <strong>This library opened May 2026 and is expanding rapidly.</strong> New
          library entries, white papers, and primary sources are being added monthly.
          <strong>Newest:</strong> an AI <a href="/reference-desk/">Librarian</a>
          answers questions about America's school trust lands using the
          Library's own content — free to Library Card holders, with
          citations to her sources.
          <a href="/updates/">See what's new this month →</a>
        </p>
      </aside>

      <section class="mt-12" aria-label="Featured entry points">
        <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
          Featured entries
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-4 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-or/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Oregon — the live test case
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              Strong constitutional architecture (1857), the Elliott State Forest decoupling
              (2017–2022), and the January 2026 Court of Appeals standing victory in
              <em>Advocates for School Trust Lands v. State of Oregon</em>. The case OASTL is
              currently litigating.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-ut/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Utah — the trust under continuous defense
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              A national model for what an active constituency does: revenue routed
              school by school produced a thirty-fold endowment growth, and a watchful
              crew of parents, teachers, and legislators defends the architecture
              against successive diversion attempts — including the one underway right
              now.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-ms/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Mississippi — the lost inheritance
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              Section 16 history shows what depletion looks like when no recovery occurred.
              Sixteenth sections sold for as little as $1 per acre in the 1820s.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-10 rounded-md border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 shadow-sm">
        <p>
          Six rooms are live today: <a href="/reading/">Reading Room</a>
          (the Library’s curated reference collection of published
          scholarship plus the Atlas of fifty state dossiers),
          <a href="/atlas/">Atlas</a>, <a href="/maps/">Map Room</a>,
          <a href="/counting/">Counting House</a>,
          <a href="/newsroom/">Newsroom</a>, and the
          <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a> — where an AI
          Librarian answers questions about America's school trust lands
          using the Library's own content. Five more rooms are
          on the floor plan and visible from the <a href="/explore/">Lobby</a>:
          the <a href="/court/">Court Room</a>,
          <a href="/breach-recovery/">Breach &amp; Recovery</a>,
          <a href="/founders/">Founders' Cabinet</a>,
          <a href="/school/">Schoolroom</a>, and the
          <a href="/lectures/">Lecture Hall</a>. Each carries a
          stub page describing what it will hold; the stubs get replaced
          in place as the rooms ship.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section
        class="mt-10 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-amber-500 bg-amber-50 p-5 shadow-sm"
        aria-label="Why some numbers are blank"
      >
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-amber-900">
          Why some numbers are blank
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-amber-900">
          You'll see "Awaiting State Disclosure" badges across this library. Twelve states
          publish complete school-trust accounting today. Thirty-eight don't. The Counting House
          makes that visible because that absence is the finding — not a defect of this site.
          Visible incompleteness with correction pathways is the fastest path to credibility, and
          it's the only way a public ledger of public trusts can earn its name.
        </p>
      </section>

      <ReferenceDesk />

      {/* v9 D.2 — lobby floor inlay. Library Mode only; Reference and
          Standard Mode hide via mode-reference.css / default base.
          The seal image lands separately (Cowork-side); onerror hides
          gracefully until then. */}
      <div class="library-seal-inlay">
        <button
          type="button"
          class="library-seal-button"
          data-seal-trigger
          aria-label="View library seal larger"
        >
          <img
            src="/seal/library-seal-v1.png"
            alt="America's School Trust Library seal"
            class="library-seal library-seal--inlay"
            onerror="this.style.display='none'"
          />
        </button>
      </div>
    </main>
    <PrepublicationFooter />
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
